There's nothing special about being "healthy." Your version of "healthy" doesn't mean anything to the person next to you. You shouldn't worry about whether someone else is being "healthy." You should worry about whether they're loved, cared for, safe, and nourished.

What I'm really saying here, friends, is that health, in itself, is a white supremacist structure designed to privilege certain people with certain characteristics and oppress everyone else until they fit into that mold.

Furthermore, healthism implies that being "healthy" is the most important thing you can be, more important than anything else, and that doing anything that does not make you "healthy" is a moral wrong.
It also posits a known state of "health" derived from studies done willingly on white people or unwillingly on non-white people.

mini 🧵 on the concept of being "healthy:" "Healthy" is not a neutral concept. It cannot stand on its own. It relies on and incorporates into itself anti-fatness, anti-Blackness, ableism, and healthism into its concept of what "healthy" is.

7/n That means taking any and all precautions that can be taken to make in-person events safer and providing robust virtual alternatives for those individuals who cannot be in-person. This will be my philosophy for events going forward.
6/n Fundamentally, I believe we each have a moral responsibility to protect each other from preventable harm as best we can and to ensure equitable, safe access for all.

5/n This is also because as a disabled person and someone at high risk for severe covid-19, I believe that I have the same right to feel safe and protected by society as ableds and low-risk people; my access to the world should not be limited b/c "safe" levels don't include me.

4/n This is because we still know too little about the long-term effects of COVID-19 infection, but we are seeing significant multisystemic impact on folks who had mild or even asymptomatic infections, even with vaccination and boosting.

3/n I believe that the NPIs available for lowering the risk of COVID-19 infection still have a primary place in our day to day lives; masking, rapid testing, ventilation, physical distancing. I'm committed to people I engage with not getting COVID from me/giving it to me.

2/n The CDC has blatantly said that they do not care if you get COVID-19; in fact, they've said that they are okay if  you get COVID-19 as long as you can (theoretically) get an antiviral immediately after (still don't have the funding approved for that yet)

If your employees are answering “nothing,” you’re in trouble.

We know, with utter certainty, that work won’t love you back. But the question, I think, is this? Does your work give you the tools to love yourself? Does it give you the ability to make the change you want to see in the world happen? What does your work give you?

I think companies who continue to invest in placelessness over placefulness - the creation of value in a place instead of outside of a place - will continue to fall behind. It’s why employees are valuing mental health, balance, and well-being so much more than extra perks.

Now, more than ever, our users, our employees, they all have found the new value of home, of steadfastness, of being in one place, of creating for oneself an oasis of community and commonality and stability, needed more than ever after the last few years.

We have been sold the idea that anything connected with fatness is lazy, including Blackness, and so we run away as fast as we can from the very things that create placeness, that create continuity, that develop history and depth and roots and *home.*
Doesn’t that feel more inviting? Isn’t that a place you would want to stay? Wouldn’t you want to continue to invest in that place, in that space, in that experience?

Now, consider the possibilities of a business model focused around abundance, satiation, comfort, care, ease, and plenty. Imagine designing experiences and hiring opportunities and workplaces that prioritize fullness, richness, depth, expansion, solidness, and growth.
All of this language is the language of white supremacy & capitalism, which only values things which contribute to the continued oppression of Fat Black people in tech.

Do you REALLY care about Black people? Because if you did, you’d have to care about fat people. You’d have to care about disabled people, who are also eliminated in your obsession with peak performance and optimization.
Do you get how your obsession with “optimizing” and “lean” software and “Agile” or “efficient” processes pathologize fatness through both language and structure? Have you even thought about it?

How, #TechTwitter, do you make sure there’s space for fat Black people in your companies, and that they are celebrated, affirmed, and given the literal space they need to feel comfortable and welcome? Do you understand the connection between anti-fatness and anti-Blackness?

I dunno, I’m glad I have @unsolicitedftb because it feels like a lotta folk on here aren’t interested in having the hard conversations in public. What are you doing to make sure #FatAndBlack people are given equal space and access at your company?

That they feel they have to get there through IWL, which is shown to have a very poor success rate, increases one's risk of other health issues, and actually increases the likelihood one will gain more weight, is a travesty.

I should add one other feeling I have towards fat people who choose IWL: Hope. 

Hope that they find the joy they are searching for, the resolution to health issues they are searching for, just hope all around.
All in all, I love fat people. I love us so much that I want us all to be as celebrated by society as thin people are, granted the right to equitable access to ALL of society and its creations.

Fat ppl who choose IWL are not "enemies," they aren't even combatants in the space *until* they unfortunately become what is most common, which is a former fat person who now embodies most of anti-fatness, using their choices as a cudgel against other fat people.

My only feeling towards fat people who choose IWL is compassion & worry. Compassion that they have been forced into this by fatphobic practices & worry that they will end up w/ other issues as a result of their IWL that they were not told about & that they still won't be happy.

One can't be for fatpol & fat lib if one does these things bc they are actively engaging in behaviors that reinforce anti-fatness in the world. It is an alignment of oneself with the idea that thinner is better, bc one can not separate one's actions from the thin gaze.

Conformity in this situation is a natural response to violence and abuse. That said, one cannot be aligned with fatpol and fat lib if one engages in IWL AND promotes it. Promoting it includes talking about your WL publicly, sharing pictures, etc.

I *love* fat people, even the ones who engage in IWL. What someone does with their body is their own personal choice. I have never debated that.  Fat people, fat Black people even moreso, get so much pressure to conform our bodies to a norm & are punished if we don't.

Listen: I don't care what anyone else thinks. I am anti-intentional weight loss as a tool to manage health. The data doesn't support the claims, full stop. This does not in ANY WAY mean I am anti-the people who engage in IWL, *especially* fat people. In fact, it's the opposite.

I read 7993 pages of books. I wrote a bajillion posts on Twitter and Facebook. I read tens of thousands of articles. I guested on one of my favorite podcasts, twice! 13/24

- I made a whole lot more internet friends

- I spent a lot of time hanging out with so many cool people, including all of you!! 11/24

- I launched a podcast with four BRILLIANT fat friends

- I started learning to program 9/24

Again, rough thoughts. Not certain about any of this, but this is how I feel today.

However, I wouldn't want Twitter to go away, or Facebook (gimme a whole new leadership structure tho, and oust Zuck), or IG, or TikTok, or Reddit. And i don't think they will. So we gotta figure something out - how to use them or modify them to be safer. What a problem.

i often go back to the idea that the human brain is just still not prepared for social media - we can't comprehend its vastness and interconnectedness, and so we shrink it in our brain to make it workable - and so we misuse it and get misused by it, bc we aren't ready.
I think you can only refine response & interruption tools & eliminate some of the most blatant abuses and harms, which there's still a lot of work that can be done there, for sure.

I'm not sure you can have one without the other, really. I don't know if  you can prevent the shitty stuff that happens here without preventing the good stuff, maybe? (virality, serendipity, connectedness)

there's so much to love about social media. I've met so many amazing people, learned so many new things, and started making impacts in ways I didn't think plausible. The permeability of boundaries is really social media's greatest strength and its greatest weakness.

But who's going to do that? It seems like Twitter is a game to get likes, I guess, which is weird, but I've definitely been like, "This might be a viral tweet" and then been disappointed when it's not.

It's why people tweeting in defense of people getting piled on show the same behavior as those who pile on - snap responses that lack nuance. It's a neverending cycle, unless someone chooses to break it.

said another way, should we be more aware of the impact our tweets have, in every direction? who is responsible, the tweeter or the replier, or both? I don't think there's an easy answer to this, and I think there's very little incentive to be thoughtful on Twitter, period.

and also, yet, is anyone surprised? could we not have predicted this? should we not tweet things that we know will get a negative response? do we hold responsibility when things go exactly the way they could be predicted to go?

(rough thoughts - absolutely not a final take here) wow. people are wild. be forgetting that capitalism requires us to work the moment someone takes a job in a sector they don't like. immediate commitment to the bit over the person.
